Ahead of the 2019 general elections, federal government has raised alarm over alleged plans by some unnamed politicians to stockpile arms that may be used to destabilize the country during the election. The Inspector General of Police, Idris Abubakar while briefing state House Correspondents after the meeting said government was concerned over the reports of “proliferation and stockpiling of weapons by some disgruntled elements with a desire to take laws into their hands at the slightest opportunity.” He disclosed that government was also concerned over possible post election violence, “as desperate politicians may whip up ethno- religious sentiments to create security situation in the country” According to him, “The meeting also discussed attempt to put pressure on electoral body by some notable personalities through demonstrations which was brought under control by combine efforts of security agencies to avoid been hijacked by hoodlums and armed bandits.”
In a statement by the Minister of Defence, Masure Dan Ali, corroborated the position of the IGP, The Minister said the Defense Council has called for concerted efforts of all security agencies to ensure that 2019 elections are hitch free The Council also said there is need for continuous sensitization of the public by National Orientation Agency (NOA) and regular meetings of relevant stakeholders including INEC, international/ local observers and the media ahead of the elections. “The meeting started by discussing the general overview of the security situation in the country as it relates to the conduct of the forthcoming 2019 general elections. “It recommended deployment of security agencies to states to enable the elections to be conducted peacefully and to further doused tension created by the outcome of the political parties’ primaries and some desperate persons to sabotage the electoral process.”  Tony Ailemen, Abuja 